[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Your books, your comics, your audiobooks, and your reading stats, all of it living on a server you control. That is Book Orbit, and it calls itself your reading space. One Docker container quietly replaces Goodreads, Calibre, a comic reader, and'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an audiobook app at the same time, with nothing ever leaving your network. But here is the part that does not add up. This project shipped its very first stable release barely a month ago. So, how is it already this complete and this'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'polished? Stick around, because the answer is honestly kind of wild. Let\'s start with the number that made me look twice. Book Orbit crossed 1,066 stars on GitHub in about a month, and it is still climbing. For a self-hosted library app'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from a brand new project, that kind of traction usually takes a year or more to build. The pitch is simple enough to explain in one breath. Take every format of book you own, drop it onto your own hardware, and read it'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anywhere, with no subscription, no third-party account, and absolutely nothing leaving your home network. People clearly wanted exactly that. The stars are the receipt, and they kept coming. And the experience is'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mobile-first, which is exactly where most self-hosted book tools fall apart. This is bookorbit.app running in a plain phone browser. No app store, no install, just open the page. You get a clean home screen, built-in'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'readers for ebooks, PDFs, comics, and audiobooks, and the same dashboard you would see on desktop, shrunk down and still completely usable with your thumb. You can flip through a graphic novel, pick up an audiobook exactly where you'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'left off, and check your reading streak from the couch. The whole reading space follows you everywhere, and it lives on your server, not somebody else\'s cloud. So, what is actually inside that one container? A lot more than you would'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expect. Book Orbit ships native web readers for ebooks, including EPUB, MOBI, and AZW3, plus PDFs, CBZ, and CBR comics, and audiobooks in M4B and MP3, with no extra plugins required. It syncs'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'both ways with Kobo e-readers and with KOReader, so your progress matches whether you read on a device or in the browser. It serves an OPDS catalog for apps like Thorium and Moon+ Reader, delivers books straight to your Kindle by email, and'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'supports multiple users with isolated libraries and single sign-on through Authentic, Keycloak, or Authelia. Most tools pick exactly one of these lanes. BookOrb quietly runs all of them at once. Put the momentum side-by-side'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it is genuinely striking. 1,066 stars, 75 forks, 10 tagged releases, and support for more than a dozen file formats across ebooks, comics, and audio. Remember, that first stable version only landed in the middle'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of May. 10 releases since then works out to a new version roughly every 3 days. This is not a weekend project coasting on a flashy readme. It is being shipped hard, completely in the open. And every one of'

[02:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these numbers is public on the repository, so you can verify all of it yourself before you ever trust it with your library. Standing it up is genuinely a coffee break job. You make a folder, pull the official Docker Compose file, and generate a couple of secrets'

[03:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with OpenSSL. One to sign login tokens and one for the database. You set the URL you will open in your browser, point it at the folder where your books already live, and run Docker Compose up. About a minute later, you have the app, a PostgreSQL database,'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and a background worker all running, and BookOrb answers on port 3000. You open the one-time setup token, create your admin account, and start dropping books in. No Calibre desktop dependency, no manual database wrangling, just a single'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'container and your own files. On the desktop, the polish really shows. The dashboard is a grid of widgets you arrange yourself with reading goals, current streaks, a heat map of when you actually read, pace charts, and genre'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breakdowns pulled from your own activity. Your shelves are not just static folders, either. Smart scopes let you build dynamic, rule-based collections. Say, every unread sci-fi book over 400 pages,'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and they update themselves automatically as your library changes. Metadata is pulled from nine providers, including Google Books, Open Library, Goodreads, Hardcover, Audible, and Comic Vine. So, covers and details fill in on their own.'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It feels less like a file browser and more like a private, genuinely beautiful version of the reading apps you already pay for. Now, the honest part. Book Orbit is not the biggest fish in this pond. Stack the major self-hosted'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reading apps by GitHub stars, and the veterans absolutely dwarf it. Calibre Web sits around 17,500 stars, Audiobookshelf near 13,200, Kavita close to 10,900, and Komga over 6,300.'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Book Orbit at roughly 20,100 is the clear new arrival. But, here\'s the twist that pays off the question from the start. Every single one of those giants specializes. Calibre Web does ebooks,'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Audiobookshelf does audio, Komga does comics. Book Orbit is the only one trying to do all of it natively, inside a single container, and it pulled this much attention in its very first month'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doing exactly that. That pace is the real story, and it is the answer to the question I planted at the very start. Book Orbit hit version 1.0 on May 13th, 2026. By June 12th, it was already on'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version 1.10. 10 releases in about 30 days. That is a new version roughly every 3 days, all in the open, with a public change log you can read line by line. A project moving this fast a month'

[05:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in is either going to flame out or become a staple. The trajectory here, plus a real company-grade live demo you can try right now without an account, points firmly at the second one. One thing to'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get straight before you deploy, because it genuinely matters. Book Orbit is licensed under AGPL 3.0, and that license has teeth most licenses do not. If you self-host it for yourself, your family, or your friends, you are'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'completely free. Run it, modify it, never share a single line of code, no strings attached. But, AGPL adds a network clause. The moment you offer a modified version to other'

[05:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people as a hosted service, you\'re obligated to make your source changes available to those users. For the vast majority of self-hosters, this changes nothing at all. But, if you are dreaming of turning it into a paid'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'product, read the license first. It is a fair deal. Just know the deal. So, that is Book Orbit, a single self-hosted container that pulls your ebooks, PDFs, comics, and audiobooks into one private'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reading space, syncs to your devices, tracks how you actually read, and is being built at a genuinely relentless pace. There is a live demo at bookorbit.app you can poke at right now without'

[06:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signing up, and the whole thing is open source on GitHub, both linked in the description below. If self-hosting your own library is your kind of thing, this is absolutely want to watch closely. Drop a comment with the format you read the most, hit'

[06:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscribe for more open source finds every single week, and I will catch you in the next one.'
